Icelandic has separate masculine, feminine and neuter words for they, when talking about a group of mixed gender people or items, the neuter form is used. Like English, the pronoun usually comes before the verb, as in the example below:


&lt;U+00E9&gt;g heiti Magn&lt;U+00FA&gt;s&lt;U+2014&gt;I am called Magn&lt;U+00FA&gt;s


But, just as easily, the order of the sentence may be inverted. In this case, the pronoun moves to the end of the sentence:


Magn&lt;U+00FA&gt;s heiti &lt;U+00E9&gt;g&lt;U+2014&gt;Magn&lt;U+00FA&gt;s I am called (or, literally Magn&lt;U+00FA&gt;s called I am)


In English, changing of the word order like this would render a phrase nonsensical. This is mainly due to the fact that whilst being a Germanic language, English has lost most of its noun declension. See syntax for more information.
